---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Best Baijiu for Beginners: How to Choose Your First Bottle';
const description = 'Choose a beginner-friendly baijiu by aroma type, proof, occasion, and budget instead of buying only by brand fame.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <header class="article-header"><div class="narrow"><p class="eyebrow">Buying Guide</p><h1>Best Baijiu for Beginners</h1><p class="lede">The best first baijiu is not always the most famous or expensive bottle. It is the bottle that matches your tolerance, food, and reason for drinking.</p></div></header>
  <section class="content"><article>
    <h2>Start With the Situation</h2><p>Are you tasting at home, bringing a gift, hosting Chinese guests, mixing cocktails, or buying for a banquet? Each situation points to a different style.</p>
    <h2>Beginner Rules</h2><ul><li>Do not start with prestige alone.</li><li>Buy from a channel you trust more than packaging you admire.</li><li>If possible, taste smaller bottles before buying premium full bottles.</li><li>Expect aroma intensity. That is part of the category, not necessarily a flaw.</li></ul>
    <h2>Safer First Choices</h2><p>For many beginners, a clean light-aroma or approachable strong-aroma baijiu is easier than jumping straight into high-proof sauce aroma. If buying Maotai-style bottles, treat them as serious tasting spirits rather than party shots.</p>
    <div class="callout">A beginner-friendly baijiu should teach you something without punishing you for being new.</div>
  </article></section>
</BaseLayout>
